college <- read.csv("ForbesAmericasTopColleges2019.2.csv")
collegeSAT <- college %>%
  mutate(SAT = (SAT.Lower + SAT.Upper)/2,
  ACT = (ACT.Lower + ACT.Upper)/2)
collegesize <- collegeSAT %>%
  mutate(collegeSAT, Size=ifelse(Student.Population <= 5000, 'Small', ifelse(Student.Population >= 15000, 'Large', ifelse(Student.Population > 5000 & Student.Population < 15000, 'Medium', NA))))

Interpretation

For our final project in Data Analytics 101 we decided to investigate a data set that was investigating the college ranking that Forbes presented in 2019. There were seventeen different variables in this data set. That ranged from rank, state, population, cost, to SAT and ACT scores. The ranking ranges from 1-650 with a mix of public and private universities included. The question that we were trying to answer while analyzing this data set, was which variables affected the ranking of the college or university the most? Our sub-question was how does the ranking of a school affect the alumni salary? [America’s Top College Top College Rankings (Forbes)],(https://www.kaggle.com/chris95cam/forbes-americas-top-colleges-2019)

Ethical considerations

Some of the stakeholders in our data analysis would be seniors and juniors in high school, professors, or parents. Specifically I think that seniors and juniors in high school would like to look at our data analysis because they could see what variables actually matter when determining the rank of a college. If they are looking to go to a top ranked school then they should understand which parts of their application are going to matter the most in relation to the ranking of a college. Professors may be interested in our analysis if they are looking for a job and want to see which schools are ranked at the top or bottom and why. With variables like annual income of alumni and grant aid those are more unique variables that would get professors and parents attention. Another ethical consideration that we have to consider is how the colleges will be affected. Since lots of people look at the ranking of colleges before committing to one, having an understanding of what determines the ranking might help or hurt the colleges. Since our data set is not dealing with private information about people we are going to have an easier time. With that being said, continuing to be transparent, honest, and consistent with our analysis are important factors that we need to keep in mind as we are conducting our data analysis.

head(college)

Manipulating the data set

collegeSAT <- college %>%
  mutate(SAT = (SAT.Lower + SAT.Upper)/2,
  ACT = (ACT.Lower + ACT.Upper)/2)

We used the function mutate to create a new column of the average ACT and SAT scores. The original data set gave us data for the SAT and ACT scores in the 25th percentile and the 75th percentile. We combined these columns using the average of both columns so that we could analyze these variables.

collegesize <- collegeSAT %>%
  mutate(collegeSAT, Size=ifelse(Student.Population <= 5000, 'Small', ifelse(Student.Population >= 15000, 'Large', ifelse(Student.Population > 5000 & Student.Population < 15000, 'Medium', NA))))

We used the function mutate to create a new column based on the size of the school. We used an if else statement to name the size of the school based on the number of students attending the school.

This histogram is just showing us the average acceptance rate of all of the colleges that are apart of the data set. This is an easier way to look at all of the acceptance rate as there are a lot of schools acceptance rates that hover around 30%. It is important to note that 30% is different for every school because some school are really small with around 1,000 kids or schools that have 65,000 kids.The dashed line that is shown in the histogram represents the average acceptance rate. From this histogram we can see that as the acceptance rate gets lower, there are less schools. Therefore there are more schools that have a higher than average acceptance rate than there are lower than average.

Boxplot

ggplot(collegesize, aes(x = Size, y = Rank)) +
geom_boxplot(fill = '#FF6699', col = 'black', notch = TRUE, outlier.color = 'gray') +
labs(y = "Ranking", x= "Size", title = "Rank Based on Size of School") +
theme_minimal()

This box plot is telling us that there is no real correlation between the size of a school and what it is ranked. The median ranking for small schools is slightly higher, meaning slightly worse than the median at large and medium sized schools.

Scatter plot

ggplot(collegesize, aes(x=Rank, y = Alumni.Salary))+
  geom_point(color="blue")+
  facet_wrap( ~ Public.Private)+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", linetype=1, color="black") +
  theme_minimal()

In this graph we can see that for public and private universities the trend is the same that as the average alumni salary rises the rank of the college gets lower. This would make sense because it is suggesting that the lower ranked schools, or “better” schools have alumni that makes a higher salary. The trend seems to be a little bit more extreme as the angle is steeper in private universities.

Scatter plot

ggplot(collegesize, aes(x= Total.Annual.Cost, y = Alumni.Salary))+
  geom_point(color = "aquamarine2") +
  facet_wrap(~ Public.Private) +
  ggtitle("Scatter Plot") + xlab("Annual Cost") + ylab("Alumni Salary") +

This line graph is showing that as the annual cost of schools increases so does the average alumni salary. Looking at the two graphs, we can see that there is a clear correlation between alumni salary and annual cost for private schools and not nearly as much of a correlation between the two with public schools. We think that this makes sense because at private schools the networking opportunities are very good and opportunities are sometimes limited to just those private schools students. Something that is also important to note is that instate public schools lost much less than private schools annually. Whereas for public schools, instate and out of state tuition does not change.

Map

staterank<-collegeSAT %>%
  group_by(State)%>%
  summarise(RankAvg=mean(Rank))
states_map <- map_data("state")
tolower(staterank)

staterank <- staterank %>%
  mutate(region = tolower(setNames(state.name, state.abb)[State]))

states_mapRank <- left_join(states_map, staterank, by = "region")

ggplot(states_mapRank, aes(long, lat, group= group))+
  geom_polygon(aes(fill = RankAvg),col="white")+
    scale_fill_viridis_c(option ="G") +
   ggtitle("Average Rank of Schools by State") +
  theme_minimal()

In this map we added up all of the ranks of all of the colleges or universities in each state. According to the map the state with the highest ranked schools technically meaning the “worse” schools is New Mexico. Then looking at the lowest ranked schools, the “better” schools it seems to be a tie between Massachusetts, Rhode Island and Connecticut. As we are looking at this map, it is important to remember that this includes outliers. Therefore if there is a state where most of the schools are ranked lower but then one is ranked higher it is going to make the state looks “worse” and on our map brighter in color.

Data explanation and exploration

Provide some details describing the data you are working with. What are the observations? The key variables you will be looking at? Are there any particular challenges in the data you will need to work through or be aware of during analysis?There are seventeen variables in our data set but we are only focusing on twelve.The key variables we will be working with are rank, state, public/private, student population, average grant aid, total annual cost, alumni salary, acceptance rate, SAT lower, SAT upper, ACT lower, and ACT upper. We are working with all of those variables as they are in their original form except for the SAT and ACT data. The upper and lower variables we are referring to are the 25th and 75th percentiles of scores that are accepted at a certain school. Instead of having to deal with four variables about SAT and ACT we decided to make two new columns where we averaged the upper and lower quartiles of each test so we could see the average score for the schools. We thought this would be easiest to work with and get the most accurate results. Something to note about our data set is that there were very few NA values so which is nice because that means our this data set has full accuracy in terms of data reported. There are not too many holes because all of the data was reported. We also made a new column using mutate.ifelse to separate the schools into small, medium and large sizes. The small schools are schools that have less than 5,000 students, medium is between 5,000 and 15,000 and the larger schools are 15,000 students or above. That includes all students, underground and graduate students. We decided to do this so that we could compare the schools by how they are categorized.

Statistical Analysis and Interpretation

Linear Regression

full_mod1 <- lm(Rank ~ Public.Private + Undergraduate.Population + Average.Grant.Aid + Total.Annual.Cost + Alumni.Salary + SAT + ACT + Acceptance.Rate, data=collegesize)

summary(full_mod1)
##

## lm(formula = Rank ~ Public.Private + Undergraduate.Population + 
##     Average.Grant.Aid + Total.Annual.Cost + Alumni.Salary + SAT + 
##     ACT + Acceptance.Rate, data = collegesize)
##

## Undergraduate.Population -1.638e-03  4.447e-04  -3.684 0.000254 ***

## 
## Residual standard error: 83.34 on 516 degrees of freedom
##   (125 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8076, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8047 
## F-statistic: 270.8 on 8 and 516 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

First beginning with the p-value, we can see that the p-value of the intercept is less than 0.05 which would suggest that we can reject the null hypothesis. In this case the null hypothesis would be that none of the variables that we put in would not have any effect on the rank of the colleges. To begin with the p- value of the public and private universities variable, the p-value is 7.75e-08 which is clearly less that 0.05 therefore it is significant and does have an affect on rank. The p-value of the average grant aid variable is 1.15e-08 which is a lot less than 0.05 therefore it is significant and does have an affect on rank.The p- value of the total annual cost variable is 1.16e-12 which means that we can reject the null hypothesis meaning that total annual cost is significant. The p-value of the alumni salary variable is 8.90e-13 which is a lot less than 0.05 therefore it is significant and does have an affect on rank.The p-value of the average SAT score variable is 0.000643 which is a lot less than 0.05 therefore it is significant and does have an affect on rank. The p-value of the average ACT score variable is 3.55e-10 which is a lot less than 0.05 therefore it is significant and does have an affect on rank. Lastly looking at the acceptance rate we can see that the p-value of acceptance rate is 0.287130 which is bigger than 0.05 therefore we can accept the null hypothesis and say that acceptance.rate has no effect on rank. Looking at the Adjusted R-Squared we can see that this linear regression is 80% representative of the results which means this regression is giving us valuable information since it is representative of so much of the data.

Correlation Test

cor.test(collegesize$Rank, collegesize$Alumni.Salary)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  collegesize$Rank and collegesize$Alumni.Salary
## t = -26.237, df = 633, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.7570629 -0.6822824
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.7217724

Looking at this correlation test we can see that the p-value is much smaller than 0.05 therefore we can reject the null hypothesis. In this case the null hypothesis would be that there is no correlation between rank and alumni salary. In looking at this correlation test we can see that the rank and alumni salary variables are highly correlated, as the correlation number is 72%. This result makes sense because if we think about the idea that lower ranked schools are “better” therefore the average alumni salary would be higher. In this case the 95% confidence interval would mean that we are 95% confident that the true mean is within -0.7570629 -0.6822824. The degrees of freedom is 633 which is good because that means there was a lot a lot data to work with so we could get the most accurate results.

Multicollinearity test

ggpairs(collegesize, columns = c("Undergraduate.Population", "Average.Grant.Aid", "Total.Annual.Cost", "Alumni.Salary", "SAT", "ACT", "Rank"))

From this correlation test, it shows us how correlated our variables are. Of the variables other than rank, the two that are the most correlated are average grant aid and total annual cost. Other variables that have a strong correlation are SAT and acceptance rate. The variables that are the most correlated with rank are SAT, alumni salary, and the acceptance rate. This confirms our predictions that the higher the SAT, the lower the rank, and as the lower the acceptance rate, the lower the rank. It also confirms that rank is correlated with alumni salary and we found that the lower the rank of the school, the higher the alumni salary.

As we have learned in class this histogram is normally distributed. It has a nice bell shaped curve to it. This histogram is just showing us our residuals in a visual form confirming that the results we got are normal.

A normally distributed residual v. fitted value plot is when the points are randomly distributed around the x axis. That means that a linear regression is appropriate and if they are not randomly distributed than a linear regression should not be run. This plot is supposed to show nonlinear relationships between outcome variables. This plot is representing heteroskedasticity. This means that the spread of residuals is not constant.

The cooks distance model helps to determine the outliers that can negatively affect the model.

Prediction model

lowrank <- data.frame(Undergraduate.Population=3000, Average.Grant.Aid=40000, Total.Annual.Cost=65000, Alumni.Salary=130000, SAT=1400, ACT=32)
mediumrank <- data.frame(Undergraduate.Population=10000, Average.Grant.Aid=30000, Total.Annual.Cost=50000, Alumni.Salary=100000, SAT=1200, ACT=28)
highrank <- data.frame(Undergraduate.Population=20000, Average.Grant.Aid=10000, Total.Annual.Cost=30000, Alumni.Salary=80000, SAT=1000, ACT=23)


mod = lm(Rank ~ Undergraduate.Population + Average.Grant.Aid + Total.Annual.Cost + Alumni.Salary + SAT + ACT, data =collegesize)

predict(mod, lowrank)
##        1 
## 46.39358
predict(mod, mediumrank)
##        1 
## 312.9677
predict(mod, highrank)
##        1 
## 557.6139

Using the predict function, we were able to test our findings and their affect on the rank of a college. We found that in schools with a lower rank, they had a low undergraduate population, a high average grant aid, a high annual cost, a high alumni salary, a high SAT and ACT. In the schools with a high rank, we found that they had a high undergraduate population, a low average grant aid, a low annual cost, a low alumni salary, and a low SAT and ACT. Our model predicted that for these conditions a low rank school would have a ranking of 46, a medium rank school would have a ranking of 312, and a high rank school would have a ranking of 557. This shows that our predictions were correct because the predicted rank matched our data.

Conclusion

What we concluded from this data analysis was that the size, average grant aid, public or private university, total annual cost, alumni salary, average SAT, and average ACT scores will all matter the most when it comes to determining the rank. This was very interesting to us because we really thought that the acceptance rate variable was going to have a much bigger impact on the ranking of the school. We thought this because that always seems to be the biggest topic of conversation and the biggest factor that people talk about. It was not surprising to see that grant aid, public versus private universities and test scores were big factors but it was nice to be able to confirm them. Through our data visualizations, we found that size has little effect on the rank of the school. This was surprising because we predicted that smaller schools would have a higher ranking. From looking at our scatter plot, we found that there was a correlation between rank and alumni salary. We found that the lower the rank was, the higher the average alumni salary was. From our second scatter plot, we found that there was a correlation between annual cost and alumni salary in private schools. Our scatter plot shows that in private schools, the more expensive the school is, the more money the alumni make. There was a very slight correlation in the public schools. Our map showed us where in the US the highest ranking schools were. We found that the northeast has an overall lowest average ranking than the rest of the country. One limitation I would say that came from analyzing the data in this way was that there was a limited amount of factors. Seventeen is a good amount of factors but we know that there are many things that would go into determining the rank of a college. I think that we answered our question of which factors are most important when determining rank but I think if we had more time with this we could have found a data set that was a little bigger and more recent. With that said we did our best with what we had and we can to a conclusion. Whether it is fully accurate or not we did our best to get the best results possible. One other limitation in our data would be the fact that they are naturally all correlated which you can see from our correlation test. We knew that before even analysing our data because of the nature of the data set but that can make it harder to come to conclusions when you know they are all related to each other one way or another. In the future I would say that one thing we could look more into is the question what variables does rank effect. We explored that a little bit as we could see that sometimes rank affected alumni salary but that would be an interesting point to look more into if we had more times or for future data analysts. Overall, we both learned a lot but analyzing this data set.
